# CV rendering parity rules

The CV renderer is the product moat. Do not improvise it.

## Source of truth

Read these documents before changing renderer logic:

- `docs/migration/ios-cv-rendering-audit.md`
- `docs/migration/web-migration-audit.md`

The iOS rendering architecture is the reference. Web should host the same rendering philosophy in the browser.

## Non-negotiable DOM contract

Generated CV HTML must preserve:

#pages → .page → .page-content → .cv-block[data-block]

Do not rename these selectors unless explicitly requested.

## Geometry

Preserve the A4 assumptions:

- CSS page size: `794px × 1123px`
- PDF paper target: `595pt × 842pt`
- Layout is authored in CSS pixels using the 96dpi → 72pt mapping.
- Do not introduce adaptive page sizes for CV output.

## Preview/export philosophy

- One HTML producer should feed preview and export.
- Do not create a separate export-only layout.
- Preview and export must share DOM, CSS, pagination rules, and geometry.
- Exported PDF quality is more important than convenience.

## Pagination

Do not simplify pagination logic.

Preserve as closely as possible:

- `sharedPaginationCSS`
- `sharedPaginationJS`
- `.cv-block` break avoidance
- `.novo-entry` splitting behavior
- education/courses/awards whole-block movement
- experience/volunteer continuation header behavior
- header orphan heuristic
- multi-page A4 flow

If pagination is changed, document the reason in `docs/migration/`.

## Templates

Structured and Essential are real templates.

Structured priority:
- preserve two-column float layout
- preserve main/support section placement
- preserve interleaving algorithm
- preserve typography scale
- preserve Jet/Mustard accent behavior
- preserve light-only print-stable output

Essential priority:
- preserve single-column layout
- preserve `sectionOrder`
- preserve accent bridge behavior
- preserve dark-mode support only if explicitly ported

## Fonts/assets

- Do not rely on remote fonts.
- No Google Fonts in renderer.
- Use deterministic local/system font stacks unless explicitly asked otherwise.

## Anti-patterns

Do not:
- create a generic resume template
- replace renderer with React components
- split preview/export into divergent implementations
- “modernize” CV layout without instruction
- change A4 geometry casually
- add remote assets to CV output
